&lt;h1 id="if-youre-so-smart-why-arent-you-happy"&gt;If You&amp;rsquo;re So Smart, Why Aren&amp;rsquo;t You Happy?&lt;/h1&gt;
&lt;p&gt;Feb 12 2020&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;You can increase your happiness without losing your drive&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Naval:&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;br&gt;
&amp;ldquo;Happiness is for stupid people.&amp;rdquo; That&amp;rsquo;s a common complaint I hear from smart overachievers. They think only dumb or lazy people can be happy. Entrepreneurs will say, &amp;ldquo;I don&amp;rsquo;t want to be happy because I want to be successful.&amp;rdquo; They worry that if they get too happy they&amp;rsquo;ll lose their desire and won&amp;rsquo;t work hard anymore.&lt;/p&gt;</description></item><item><title>The Power (and Peril) of Praising Your Kids -- New York Magazine - Nymag</title><link>https://linguista.cn/terencetao/career-advice/orig/the-power-and-peril-of-praising-your-kids-new-york-magazine-nymag/</link><pubDate>Fri, 09 Feb 2007 09:53:00 -0500</pubDate><guid>https://linguista.cn/terencetao/career-advice/orig/the-power-and-peril-of-praising-your-kids-new-york-magazine-nymag/</guid><description>&lt;p&gt;&lt;a href="https://linguista.cn/terencetao/career-advice/zh/the-power-and-peril-of-praising-your-kids-new-york-magazine-nymag.zh/"&gt;中文版本&lt;/a&gt;
